MATERIALIZED VIEWS :-
====================

 => a m.view is also a db object that stores query output  or precomputed result.

 => Queries performs complex group by ,joins and aggregate operations on table   
      contains huge amount of data takes more time to run then create m.view
      and store the output in m.view and whenever we want that output instead of 
      executing query on table execute query on m.view
 
 => m.views are created to improve the performance of complex operations 
 
 Granting permission to create m.view :-
 -------------------------------------------------------

  SYSTEM :-
  ----------------

SQL>GRANT CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW TO BATCH54 ;

Ex :- 

  SQL> CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW MV1
            AS
            SELECT deptno,SUM(sal) as totsal
            FROM emp 
            GROUP BY deptno ;

  => oracle creates m.view MV1 and stores query output  and whenever we want dept wise 
        total sal then execute the following query 

           SELECT * FROM MV1 ; 

	 DEPTNO     TOTSAL
	---------- 	   ----------
       	 30      	   9400
       	 10      	   8750
       	 20     	  10875

 Refreshing m.view :-
 ================

 => If base table data changes by default m.view is not updated and updating m.view is called
      refreshing m.view

           TABLE===========REFRESH===============>MV
                                            (applying changes)

  => m.view can be refreshed in 3 ways 

    1   Manually
    2   Automatically
    3   Periodically
 
 Manually :-
 ---------------

  =>  To refresh m.view manually execute the following procedure

          EXECUTE DBMS_M.VIEW.REFRESH(M.VIEW NAME);

 Ex :- 

   step 1 :-   update base table

   SQL>UPDATE emp SET sal = sal + 1000; 

  step 2 :- refresh m.view

   SQL>EXECUTE DBMS_MVIEW.REFRESH('MV1');

  step 3 :-  display m.view 

  SQL>SELECT * FROM MV1 ;

    DEPTNO     TOTSAL
    ---------        - ----------
        30      15400
        10      11750
        20      15875

 Automatically :-
 =============
 
  => once changes made to base table are committed then m.view is refreshed automatically

Ex :-

   CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW MV2 
   REFRESH ON COMMIT
   AS
   SELECT deptno,SUM(sal) as totsal
   FROM emp 
   GROUP BY deptno ;

 SELECT * FROM MV2 ;

    DEPTNO     TOTSAL
     ---------      - ----------
        30      15400
        10      11750
        20      15875
 
Test :-
---------

 step 1 :-  update base table

 SQL> UPDATE emp SET sal = sal - 1000 ;

 step 2 :-  commit the changes 

  SQL>COMMIT;

 step 3 :- display m.view

   SELECT * FROM MV2;

    DEPTNO     TOTSAL
    ----------       ----------
        30          9400
        10          8750
        20         10875

  Periodically :-
  -------------------

   => refreshing m.views based on time periods like  day,week,month,quarter,year etc

   CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW MV3
   REFRESH FORCE
   START WITH SYSDATE NEXT SYSDATE + 1
   AS
   SELECT deptno,SUM(sal) as totsal
   FROM emp 
   GROUP BY deptno ;

 BEGIN
     DBMS_SCHEDULER.CREATE_JOB (
    job_name      => 'REFRESH_MV',
    start_date    => TO_TIMESTAMP_TZ('2026/03/14','yyyy/mm/dd'),  
    repeat_interval => 'FREQ=DAILY; BYHOUR=1,6,12,18; BYMINUTE=0', -- Run at 1 AM, 6 AM, 12 PM, 6 PM daily
    job_class     => 'DEFAULT_JOB_CLASS',
    job_type      => 'PLSQL_BLOCK',
    job_action    => 'BEGIN DBMS_MVIEW.REFRESH(''MV3'',''C''); END;',  
    comments      => 'Job to refresh materialized view MV_NAME at specific times.'
  );
END;
/

